1
00:00:06,029 --> 00:00:07,630
Hi, I'm Josh Manke.

2
00:00:07,630 --> 00:00:09,412
Thanks for coming and welcome to my talk

3
00:00:09,412 --> 00:00:11,414
on matchmaking for engagements.

4
00:00:11,414 --> 00:00:14,357
Hopefully you'll enjoy this and it'll be engaging for you.

5
00:00:14,357 --> 00:00:16,639
So let's get into the talk.

6
00:00:16,639 --> 00:00:18,981
So first let's define what matchmaking is.

7
00:00:18,981 --> 00:00:21,684
We're talking about the kind of matchmaking

8
00:00:21,684 --> 00:00:23,786
where players in multiplayer games

9
00:00:23,786 --> 00:00:26,229
want to get in matches to compete with each other.

10
00:00:26,229 --> 00:00:29,011
So you have a group of players, they wanna play.

11
00:00:29,661 --> 00:00:33,164
They submit some information to the matchmaker about themselves

12
00:00:33,164 --> 00:00:35,786
that the matchmaker can use to create a good match.

13
00:00:35,786 --> 00:00:38,889
The matchmaker takes this information about many people

14
00:00:38,889 --> 00:00:43,433
and then puts them into matches and creates teams for them to play.

15
00:00:43,433 --> 00:00:45,035
OK, now, so what is engagement?

16
00:00:45,035 --> 00:00:48,998
Well, the dictionary tells us that engagement means to be greatly interested.

17
00:00:48,998 --> 00:00:52,481
And so we want our players to be greatly interested in our games.

18
00:00:52,481 --> 00:00:54,603
And this is accomplished through gameplay.

19
00:00:55,225 --> 00:01:00,912
Matchmaking is there to guarantee that the gameplay is experienced as intended by the players.

20
00:01:00,912 --> 00:01:04,557
So a lot of the time we're just preventing disengagement

21
00:01:04,557 --> 00:01:08,282
by making sure that players can play the gameplay and have a good time with it.

22
00:02:14,050 --> 00:02:15,930
So now on a good question to ask is,

23
00:02:15,930 --> 00:02:18,731
how is matchmaking then related to engagement?

24
00:02:18,731 --> 00:02:19,812
So we'll go back to our players.

25
00:02:19,812 --> 00:02:20,892
They wanna get into a match.

26
00:02:20,892 --> 00:02:23,773
Here they are, they jump through matchmaking,

27
00:02:23,773 --> 00:02:26,094
matchmaking puts them into a game,

28
00:02:26,094 --> 00:02:27,454
they enjoy your engaging gameplay,

29
00:02:27,454 --> 00:02:30,656
and then afterwards they jump back into matchmaking

30
00:02:30,656 --> 00:02:33,877
because they are engaged and they want to keep playing.

31
00:02:33,877 --> 00:02:36,438
Now, where matchmaking comes into this though,

32
00:02:36,438 --> 00:02:39,139
is what happens if they go into a game,

33
00:02:39,139 --> 00:02:41,780
but the latency is so high on that server they're playing on

34
00:02:41,780 --> 00:02:43,740
that they can't really play the game right.

35
00:02:44,248 --> 00:02:45,929
that could disengage them.

36
00:02:45,929 --> 00:02:49,810
Or maybe they're just not good enough to enjoy the gameplay.

37
00:02:49,810 --> 00:02:52,831
They're so bad compared to the other players in the match

38
00:02:52,831 --> 00:02:56,532
that they aren't even able to play very much.

39
00:02:56,532 --> 00:02:59,893
Or what happens if they just wait so long

40
00:02:59,893 --> 00:03:01,734
that they never actually get to the gameplay?

41
00:03:01,734 --> 00:03:04,915
So these are some things that we tend to try to prevent

42
00:03:04,915 --> 00:03:06,555
and avoid with matchmaking.

43
00:03:07,482 --> 00:03:09,304
We want to cause those to not happen.

44
00:03:09,304 --> 00:03:12,286
But a good question is, how important

45
00:03:12,286 --> 00:03:13,928
are each of these characteristics?

46
00:03:13,928 --> 00:03:16,810
Latency, fairness, wait times.

47
00:03:16,810 --> 00:03:18,372
Which ones are more important?

48
00:03:18,372 --> 00:03:19,833
That's what we're going to get to next

49
00:03:19,833 --> 00:03:22,035
and what I'm going to want to talk about a bit.

50
00:03:22,035 --> 00:03:24,937
But first of all, a good question we can ask

51
00:03:24,937 --> 00:03:26,679
is, why do we care what's important?

52
00:03:26,679 --> 00:03:29,601
Can't we just throw it all into the matchmaker,

53
00:03:29,601 --> 00:03:32,083
let the matchmaker just sort it out?

54
00:03:32,083 --> 00:03:33,765
And the answer is, not really.

55
00:03:33,765 --> 00:03:34,185
And here's why.

56
00:03:36,231 --> 00:03:40,233
We create a situation if we do that called having too many buckets.

57
00:03:40,233 --> 00:03:42,974
So as a player we want to matchmake on skill, say.

58
00:03:42,974 --> 00:03:46,316
That's already reducing the number of players that I can matchmake with.

59
00:03:46,316 --> 00:03:49,657
Let's say my skill bucket is only 15% of the whole population, okay?

60
00:03:49,657 --> 00:03:53,839
But now, and then we're like, well we also need to be careful with latency.

61
00:03:53,839 --> 00:03:57,621
So that's another, it's only 10% of players that I can match with because of

62
00:03:57,621 --> 00:04:01,583
my latency. And then we want to do some fun, fancy,

63
00:04:01,583 --> 00:04:03,904
cute, reputation matchmaking.

64
00:04:04,380 --> 00:04:06,021
and let's say there's only 5% of the players

65
00:04:06,021 --> 00:04:08,261
that my reputation makes me able to match with.

66
00:04:08,261 --> 00:04:11,982
Once we've broken out all these different buckets of players,

67
00:04:11,982 --> 00:04:14,703
we've reduced that player from being able to match

68
00:04:14,703 --> 00:04:19,104
with the whole population to just 0.08% of the population.

69
00:04:19,104 --> 00:04:21,385
Suddenly, even a large population

70
00:04:21,385 --> 00:04:23,205
becomes very small if you do that.

71
00:04:23,205 --> 00:04:24,785
That's why you need to be careful

72
00:04:24,785 --> 00:04:28,726
about just letting the matchmaker do it at once.

73
00:04:28,726 --> 00:04:30,607
Because we used Halo 5 for the analysis

74
00:04:30,607 --> 00:04:32,247
in this presentation,

75
00:04:32,247 --> 00:04:33,948
I'll quickly review what Halo 5 is about.

76
00:04:34,564 --> 00:04:36,145
So Halo 5 is a first-person shooter.

77
00:04:36,145 --> 00:04:39,228
It's the matches and data we used

78
00:04:39,228 --> 00:04:40,429
came from competitive matches.

79
00:04:40,429 --> 00:04:43,051
It's most of them are team-based.

80
00:04:43,051 --> 00:04:45,934
It's usually four versus four,

81
00:04:45,934 --> 00:04:47,395
but it can go up to 12 versus 12.

82
00:04:47,395 --> 00:04:51,379
A lot of our matches are team deathmatch,

83
00:04:51,379 --> 00:04:53,561
although there are some objective matches as well.

84
00:04:56,433 --> 00:05:03,196
Now because skill and fairness are often some of the more important characteristics we tend to matchmake on,

85
00:05:03,196 --> 00:05:04,796
I'll do a quick skill system review.

86
00:05:04,796 --> 00:05:09,538
This talk is not going to go in-depth on skill systems, because that would take forever,

87
00:05:09,538 --> 00:05:13,279
but it is worth reviewing them to understand how they work into matchmaking.

88
00:05:13,279 --> 00:05:16,940
So we have a player, but we want to know how good that player is.

89
00:05:16,940 --> 00:05:21,462
So we put a number on them. That number should represent their skill.

90
00:05:21,462 --> 00:05:21,802
Now,

91
00:05:22,393 --> 00:05:25,755
we use the skill to compare players to other players.

92
00:05:25,755 --> 00:05:29,816
So given two players, we can then figure out the difference in their skill from

93
00:05:29,816 --> 00:05:32,637
each other. Now a good skill system, if it's working

94
00:05:32,637 --> 00:05:38,359
right, the player with the higher skill should win most of the time. We also want

95
00:05:38,359 --> 00:05:40,719
to take this same concept to the team level.

96
00:05:40,719 --> 00:05:44,941
And one way, simple way to do that, for this talk at least,

97
00:05:44,941 --> 00:05:49,422
is just to take the average of each team. Take their average skill, average the

98
00:05:49,422 --> 00:05:51,823
numbers on both sides and then take the gap between them.

99
00:05:52,549 --> 00:05:55,390
And I call this the team skill gap.

100
00:05:55,390 --> 00:05:58,711
And it helps tell us which team is going to win most of the time.

101
00:05:58,711 --> 00:06:04,413
Now we care about that team skill gap because that tells us how fair the

102
00:06:04,413 --> 00:06:07,333
match is. If the players have the perception that

103
00:06:07,333 --> 00:06:10,214
they can win the match or not, that is probably important to them.

104
00:06:10,214 --> 00:06:14,496
But there's another type of fairness or another type of skill gap we care about

105
00:06:14,496 --> 00:06:15,856
besides the team skill gap.

106
00:06:16,525 --> 00:06:18,146
And that focuses on a single player

107
00:06:18,146 --> 00:06:19,988
and their experience in the match.

108
00:06:19,988 --> 00:06:21,549
We want to know what's gonna happen

109
00:06:21,549 --> 00:06:23,010
when this player comes around the corner

110
00:06:23,010 --> 00:06:24,871
and runs into another player on the other team.

111
00:06:24,871 --> 00:06:27,553
Are they gonna have some success against that player?

112
00:06:27,553 --> 00:06:29,614
Are they gonna feel overwhelmed?

113
00:06:29,614 --> 00:06:32,856
And to represent this, we reduce the team,

114
00:06:32,856 --> 00:06:35,838
the other team's skill again to an average.

115
00:06:35,838 --> 00:06:38,720
And we just compare the player on one team

116
00:06:38,720 --> 00:06:40,762
to the other team's average skill

117
00:06:40,762 --> 00:06:42,623
to get an average feel for what's gonna happen

118
00:06:42,623 --> 00:06:45,165
when the red player encounters a blue player.

119
00:06:45,616 --> 00:06:47,917
And in this case, again, that should feel pretty good

120
00:06:47,917 --> 00:06:51,239
because the blue player has a skill that is higher

121
00:06:51,239 --> 00:06:53,100
than the other team's average.

122
00:06:53,100 --> 00:06:55,201
And in this talk, I'll call that the personal gap,

123
00:06:55,201 --> 00:06:56,281
the personal skill gap.

124
00:06:56,281 --> 00:06:59,263
So we have two pretty important skill gaps we care about,

125
00:06:59,263 --> 00:07:02,485
the team skill gap and the personal skill gap.

126
00:07:03,554 --> 00:07:08,175
So now what we want to talk about is how important are these different characteristics?

127
00:07:08,175 --> 00:07:11,656
We've talked about skill, we've talked a little bit about latency,

128
00:07:11,656 --> 00:07:15,937
wait time, and you've probably also heard of people being worried about losing streaks.

129
00:07:15,937 --> 00:07:20,818
These points here are some of the more commonly used items in matchmaking,

130
00:07:20,818 --> 00:07:23,479
or at least items that developers tend to think are important.

131
00:07:23,479 --> 00:07:25,659
So the question is, are they really important?

132
00:07:25,659 --> 00:07:28,900
And that's what this presentation is going to try to find out.

133
00:07:28,900 --> 00:07:31,861
So how do you find out if something is important?

134
00:07:32,413 --> 00:07:36,034
The sort of industry standard these days is to use something called A-B testing.

135
00:07:36,034 --> 00:07:40,075
But the problem is matchmaking actually breaks A-B testing.

136
00:07:40,075 --> 00:07:43,536
I'll go maybe a little into that later, but it has an issue with it.

137
00:07:43,536 --> 00:07:47,878
And so we can't just use off-the-shelf A-B testing to test what's important.

138
00:07:47,878 --> 00:07:51,018
But we can do something called an observational study.

139
00:07:51,619 --> 00:07:57,021
In this case, we could look in our already existing data and find situations that match what we would like to test.

140
00:07:57,021 --> 00:08:00,722
We find matches where the ping was really bad and see how players reacted.

141
00:08:00,722 --> 00:08:05,984
Or we find really unfair matches or really fair matches and see what the players did afterwards.

142
00:08:05,984 --> 00:08:10,305
So we still have some very powerful tools to use and to be honest a lot of the most

143
00:08:10,305 --> 00:08:13,826
important studies that have been done in science have been more observational

144
00:08:13,826 --> 00:08:17,207
than more controlled experiments like A-B testing.

145
00:08:18,532 --> 00:08:20,533
So let's start with the personal skill gap.

146
00:08:20,533 --> 00:08:23,535
Again, that's where I'm a player, I run around the corner,

147
00:08:23,535 --> 00:08:26,557
I see an enemy, and will I have any success

148
00:08:26,557 --> 00:08:29,459
against that enemy when I have an encounter with them?

149
00:08:29,459 --> 00:08:32,441
The idea being, if personal skill gap is really important,

150
00:08:32,441 --> 00:08:36,064
what can we observe in our data to see if it is important?

151
00:08:36,064 --> 00:08:38,185
Well, one theory is if it's really important,

152
00:08:38,185 --> 00:08:40,707
then players will play more matches

153
00:08:40,707 --> 00:08:42,789
when the personal skill gap is smaller.

154
00:08:42,789 --> 00:08:44,130
As long as they have some success

155
00:08:44,130 --> 00:08:46,111
and they're able to play the game, they'll play more.

156
00:08:46,575 --> 00:08:51,576
So to further illustrate this, we have a player who plays a lot of matches,

157
00:08:51,576 --> 00:08:55,257
and he's playing a lot of matches because the gap, the personal gap from match to

158
00:08:55,257 --> 00:08:57,918
match was small. So he was happy. He kept playing.

159
00:08:57,918 --> 00:09:02,379
We contrast this with a player who has matches that have large personal gaps.

160
00:09:02,379 --> 00:09:05,360
This player is more angry. He's going to play less matches.

161
00:09:05,360 --> 00:09:08,060
So we should be able to construct an observation,

162
00:09:08,060 --> 00:09:12,102
pull some data out and see if we actually notice this in our data.

163
00:09:13,446 --> 00:09:17,449
So we'll go into our data and we'll see what actually happens and see if

164
00:09:17,449 --> 00:09:20,530
players do play more matches when those gaps are lower.

165
00:09:20,530 --> 00:09:23,933
So we grab a player, grab all of our players, but let's just

166
00:09:23,933 --> 00:09:27,635
for example show what happens with one player. We grab Bob. Bob's played several

167
00:09:27,635 --> 00:09:30,096
matches, so we know how many he's played here.

168
00:09:30,096 --> 00:09:33,939
Now we know Bob's played seven matches and now we want to see what was the gap

169
00:09:33,939 --> 00:09:37,701
in those matches, right? So we write down what the personal gap

170
00:09:37,701 --> 00:09:41,143
was for Bob in all those matches. Now if we do this for all of our players

171
00:09:41,143 --> 00:09:42,544
we can start to build a data set.

172
00:09:43,362 --> 00:09:44,943
That data set kind of looks like this.

173
00:09:44,943 --> 00:09:47,805
We want to know for every player,

174
00:09:47,805 --> 00:09:50,467
what was the average personal gap they experienced

175
00:09:50,467 --> 00:09:52,548
across all their matches that month?

176
00:09:52,548 --> 00:09:53,849
Like ideally that would be low.

177
00:09:53,849 --> 00:09:56,491
And then see how many matches they actually played

178
00:09:56,491 --> 00:09:59,253
and see if there's a connection between those.

179
00:09:59,253 --> 00:10:00,093
So write down Bob,

180
00:10:00,093 --> 00:10:03,236
we've already said that he's played seven matches.

181
00:10:03,236 --> 00:10:04,617
We average those gaps out

182
00:10:04,617 --> 00:10:07,458
and we see that the average across those values is 67.

183
00:10:07,458 --> 00:10:11,101
So Bob has had a gap of 67 and played seven matches.

184
00:10:11,525 --> 00:10:13,687
We then do this for other players like Alice.

185
00:10:13,687 --> 00:10:16,271
Alice had a higher skill gap, personal one,

186
00:10:16,271 --> 00:10:18,173
in those matches that she played,

187
00:10:18,173 --> 00:10:19,575
and she tended to play less matches.

188
00:10:19,575 --> 00:10:20,416
Maybe that's related.

189
00:10:20,416 --> 00:10:23,059
So we'll keep doing that across everybody

190
00:10:23,059 --> 00:10:24,121
who played for the whole month.

191
00:10:25,760 --> 00:10:27,820
And then we wanna bucket those

192
00:10:27,820 --> 00:10:29,321
to make it a bit easier to graph.

193
00:10:29,321 --> 00:10:31,461
So we can't just plot them all on a graph.

194
00:10:31,461 --> 00:10:32,982
We could, but it could be kind of confusing.

195
00:10:32,982 --> 00:10:33,982
We wanna find a trend though.

196
00:10:33,982 --> 00:10:37,003
So instead, we take all the players who say

197
00:10:37,003 --> 00:10:40,384
had a personal average skill gap of 50 for that whole month.

198
00:10:40,384 --> 00:10:43,545
And then we average how many matches did all the players

199
00:10:43,545 --> 00:10:45,646
with a skill gap between say 50 and 100,

200
00:10:45,646 --> 00:10:47,726
how many matches did they play?

201
00:10:47,726 --> 00:10:49,587
Well, they played 100, so we'll write that down.

202
00:10:49,587 --> 00:10:52,528
And then we'll do that for all of the other buckets.

203
00:10:52,528 --> 00:10:53,788
For each bucket, we'll keep note

204
00:10:53,788 --> 00:10:55,408
of how many matches the player played.

205
00:10:55,929 --> 00:10:58,130
if they had an average personal skill gap.

206
00:10:58,130 --> 00:11:00,951
So again, we're connecting what was my personal skill gap

207
00:11:00,951 --> 00:11:02,792
experience to the number of matches I played.

208
00:11:02,792 --> 00:11:04,353
And so we did that and we graphed it.

209
00:11:04,353 --> 00:11:06,034
Let's see what it looked like.

210
00:11:06,034 --> 00:11:09,255
So if you look at this graph, you're like, wow.

211
00:11:09,255 --> 00:11:13,097
You'll notice that as that average skill gap

212
00:11:13,097 --> 00:11:14,558
goes close to zero,

213
00:11:14,558 --> 00:11:17,019
meaning the perfect sort of matchmaking

214
00:11:17,019 --> 00:11:18,620
of perfect fairness for the player,

215
00:11:18,620 --> 00:11:21,942
the number of games the player's playing is the highest.

216
00:11:21,942 --> 00:11:24,803
They'll play more games if we keep that gap low.

217
00:11:25,476 --> 00:11:26,597
So you might think, well, we're done.

218
00:11:26,597 --> 00:11:29,939
We've shown that personal skill gap is definitely important.

219
00:11:29,939 --> 00:11:32,961
The problem is we're not done.

220
00:11:32,961 --> 00:11:36,363
This is bogus. And let me explain why.

221
00:11:36,363 --> 00:11:40,646
So whenever you do an observational study,

222
00:11:40,646 --> 00:11:43,588
a good sort of trick you should try first is to reverse

223
00:11:43,588 --> 00:11:46,770
whatever your hypothesis was, whatever your theory was,

224
00:11:46,770 --> 00:11:50,352
and make sure that that reversed hypothesis can't also be a thing.

225
00:11:51,062 --> 00:11:56,026
So in this case, our original hypothesis was if the average gap is small,

226
00:11:56,026 --> 00:11:59,970
players will play more matches. So if we reverse that,

227
00:11:59,970 --> 00:12:02,272
we ask if players play more matches,

228
00:12:02,272 --> 00:12:07,296
will that make the average skill gap that they play smaller?

229
00:12:07,296 --> 00:12:10,539
And the answer is yes, it will, because we are in Halo 5,

230
00:12:10,539 --> 00:12:14,983
we are skill matching. So on average, as you play more matches,

231
00:12:14,983 --> 00:12:17,085
the average will tend towards zero.

232
00:12:17,598 --> 00:12:20,519
If you just get a one-off match here or there, it may be extreme.

233
00:12:20,519 --> 00:12:22,039
You may have some one-offs there.

234
00:12:22,039 --> 00:12:25,420
And so we may find players who have these random matches out there

235
00:12:25,420 --> 00:12:29,301
who only played one game, but we don't know if they only played one game

236
00:12:29,301 --> 00:12:33,882
because the match was bad or if the match just happened to be an outlier

237
00:12:33,882 --> 00:12:35,903
and they only just happened to play one game.

238
00:12:35,903 --> 00:12:39,383
And it's because they didn't play a lot of games, it didn't average out.

239
00:12:39,383 --> 00:12:41,884
So we can't use this approach right now.

240
00:12:41,884 --> 00:12:44,605
And that brings up a general thing to be careful of.

241
00:12:44,605 --> 00:12:46,665
You want to make sure that whatever your metric is.

242
00:12:47,260 --> 00:12:49,201
It's the effect and not the cause.

243
00:12:49,201 --> 00:12:51,884
So our metric is an average matches played.

244
00:12:51,884 --> 00:12:56,368
Unfortunately, playing more matches causes better matchmaking.

245
00:12:56,368 --> 00:12:58,429
So we can't use that approach, unfortunately.

