The question is, can we go beyond though, just what happens in a match?

487
00:24:50,696 --> 00:24:54,060
Because maybe a player quits and maybe he goes and plays again.

488
00:24:54,060 --> 00:24:56,583
Yes, it does kind of ruin the match for everyone else,

489
00:24:56,583 --> 00:25:00,127
but we still want to know, can we go beyond just a player leaving a single match?

490
00:25:00,127 --> 00:25:02,770
And the answer is yeah, we can take a player,

491
00:25:02,770 --> 00:25:05,173
we can observe them going into matchmaking,

492
00:25:05,173 --> 00:25:06,735
they experience the gameplay.

493
00:25:07,772 --> 00:25:10,652
Hopefully they're engaged, that personal skill gap is small,

494
00:25:10,652 --> 00:25:13,053
so they keep playing match after match.

495
00:25:13,053 --> 00:25:15,534
Now, in theory, if that's not the case,

496
00:25:15,534 --> 00:25:17,274
they would stop playing for the night.

497
00:25:17,274 --> 00:25:20,975
They may finish the match, they may not even quit out of it,

498
00:25:20,975 --> 00:25:23,216
but because of their experience in that match,

499
00:25:23,216 --> 00:25:24,797
they may decide that they don't want to play

500
00:25:24,797 --> 00:25:25,957
any more Halo 5 that night.

501
00:25:25,957 --> 00:25:27,897
And this is also important to us,

502
00:25:27,897 --> 00:25:29,338
maybe even more important,

503
00:25:29,338 --> 00:25:32,239
because if players are quitting not just out of matches,

504
00:25:32,239 --> 00:25:33,919
but out of your entire game,

505
00:25:33,919 --> 00:25:36,180
it's kind of ruining your population overall

506
00:25:36,180 --> 00:25:37,400
and just making the game worse.

507
00:25:38,915 --> 00:25:41,277
So we want to go and measure this basically.

508
00:25:41,277 --> 00:25:44,438
We want to see, are players not quitting just the match,

509
00:25:44,438 --> 00:25:46,299
but do they leave for the night?

510
00:25:46,299 --> 00:25:49,040
Because if, say, personal skill gap is important,

511
00:25:49,040 --> 00:25:50,481
wouldn't they stop playing?

512
00:25:50,481 --> 00:25:51,922
So how do we do that?

513
00:25:51,922 --> 00:25:53,743
Well, we set it up very similarly

514
00:25:53,743 --> 00:25:55,303
to our other experiments already.

515
00:25:55,868 --> 00:25:58,429
We get each of our players, we've got Alice here.

516
00:25:58,429 --> 00:26:00,690
We know what her team skill gap was for that match,

517
00:26:00,690 --> 00:26:02,970
or we know what her personal gap was for that match.

518
00:26:02,970 --> 00:26:05,571
And instead of asking, did they stop playing,

519
00:26:05,571 --> 00:26:07,591
did they leave the match early?

520
00:26:07,591 --> 00:26:09,932
We ask, did they stop playing for eight hours?

521
00:26:09,932 --> 00:26:12,973
Or did they take off and not show up again?

522
00:26:12,973 --> 00:26:15,313
And we look in this case that Alice had a match

523
00:26:15,313 --> 00:26:17,754
with a gap of 100 and she kept playing.

524
00:26:17,754 --> 00:26:20,514
Whereas Bob had a gap of 250 and he stopped playing.

525
00:26:20,514 --> 00:26:22,795
And we wanna average this over all of our population,

526
00:26:22,795 --> 00:26:23,875
our players, our matches.

527
00:26:24,456 --> 00:26:30,521
bucket it again and graph it and see if the skill gap not only causes quits out of matches,

528
00:26:30,521 --> 00:26:32,482
but does it cause them to quit out of the game?

529
00:26:32,482 --> 00:26:37,347
And it turns out it does cause them to leave the game for the night. As this personal skill gap,

530
00:26:37,347 --> 00:26:42,371
that's what this one is, as the personal skill gap increases,

531
00:26:42,371 --> 00:26:48,136
so does the chance that a player will not only quit out of a match, but they may leave the game for the night.

532
00:26:48,677 --> 00:26:52,000
And this can go to be as high as a 40% chance

533
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:54,502
that a player is going to turn off the game for the night

534
00:26:54,502 --> 00:26:56,984
because of a large personal gap.

535
00:26:56,984 --> 00:26:59,607
Which means it's very important to our players

536
00:26:59,607 --> 00:27:02,329
to not have matches where they are so much worse

537
00:27:02,329 --> 00:27:04,451
than the other team that they can't really engage.

538
00:27:04,451 --> 00:27:07,954
So let's look at the takeaway from that.

539
00:27:07,954 --> 00:27:09,916
The takeaways are kind of the obvious ones, right?

540
00:27:09,916 --> 00:27:12,198
Players will disengage if the personal skill gap

541
00:27:12,198 --> 00:27:12,899
is too large.

542
00:27:13,458 --> 00:27:16,599
And we can again, use these graphs to tune

543
00:27:16,599 --> 00:27:19,220
and pick what type of personal skill gaps

544
00:27:19,220 --> 00:27:22,561
or team skill gaps are okay for our players.

545
00:27:22,561 --> 00:27:25,902
And again, the nice thing about this is we can go beyond

546
00:27:25,902 --> 00:27:28,463
just looking at one match.

547
00:27:28,463 --> 00:27:31,003
Now, I want to switch gears a little bit

548
00:27:31,003 --> 00:27:33,464
and talk about a more controversial topic

549
00:27:33,464 --> 00:27:36,405
that comes up once you start digging into this data.

550
00:27:36,405 --> 00:27:39,626
And that deals around stacked parties.

551
00:27:39,626 --> 00:27:41,027
The question here being,

552
00:27:42,225 --> 00:27:44,907
you got what I call a pre-made stacked party.

553
00:27:44,907 --> 00:27:47,989
This is a group of four friends who are playing together in the party.

554
00:27:47,989 --> 00:27:51,290
When they go into matchmaking, they go in together, and that's fine.

555
00:27:51,290 --> 00:27:53,772
The issue here is that these aren't just four

556
00:27:53,772 --> 00:27:58,855
average players or even four very good players. These are like

557
00:27:58,855 --> 00:28:01,956
four of your best players. They've decided they're friends, they're going to

558
00:28:01,956 --> 00:28:05,718
get together and play, and what this causes is they will play

559
00:28:05,718 --> 00:28:06,979
against another group

560
00:28:07,598 --> 00:28:11,839
potentially, another pre-made group, a party of friends that are playing together,

561
00:28:11,839 --> 00:28:17,120
and that party could be very good, but they're just nowhere near as good as that stacked party.

562
00:28:17,120 --> 00:28:22,521
And what happens is that the stacked party will stop that pre-made party, beat them very badly,

563
00:28:22,521 --> 00:28:28,942
and this leads to, if we believe our data already, players disengaging. And not just disengaging

564
00:28:28,942 --> 00:28:35,084
out of the match, because, and to be honest, players do quit less out of matches while

565
00:28:35,084 --> 00:28:37,024
they're in parties, like this good party here.

566
00:28:37,720 --> 00:28:39,801
but it will still cause them to disengage

567
00:28:39,801 --> 00:28:42,523
out of the game entirely, which is even worse.

568
00:28:42,523 --> 00:28:43,604
So what can you do about that?

569
00:28:43,604 --> 00:28:45,005
Because it's, and I'll give you a hint

570
00:28:45,005 --> 00:28:46,185
that there's not a lot.

571
00:28:46,185 --> 00:28:48,067
There's not a lot of great solutions

572
00:28:48,067 --> 00:28:49,207
at this point to what you do.

573
00:28:49,207 --> 00:28:52,870
You can ask yourself, well, should we just not allow

574
00:28:52,870 --> 00:28:53,951
those stacked parties?

575
00:28:53,951 --> 00:28:57,773
Because they're gonna be scaring players out of our games.

576
00:28:57,773 --> 00:29:01,176
And if you do that, you end up making

577
00:29:01,176 --> 00:29:02,156
some of your best players,

578
00:29:02,156 --> 00:29:04,037
so you're making it so they can't play together.

579
00:29:04,037 --> 00:29:05,518
And that's probably gonna make them sad.

580
00:29:07,025 --> 00:29:09,386
But if you allow the stacked parties,

581
00:29:09,386 --> 00:29:10,527
you're being unfair potentially

582
00:29:10,527 --> 00:29:12,207
to everyone else they play against,

583
00:29:12,207 --> 00:29:14,288
which is a much larger group than the small group

584
00:29:14,288 --> 00:29:16,969
of stacked players that want to play together.

585
00:29:16,969 --> 00:29:20,110
And again, there's no super great solution here,

586
00:29:20,110 --> 00:29:23,991
but I will just demonstrate what this can cause.

587
00:29:23,991 --> 00:29:25,552
So if you allow these stacked parties,

588
00:29:25,552 --> 00:29:26,712
at least I've observed in our data,

589
00:29:26,712 --> 00:29:30,293
I've gone and just watched some specific stacked parties

590
00:29:30,293 --> 00:29:32,394
and seen what their effect on the population has been.

591
00:29:32,955 --> 00:29:36,936
you can actually watch a single party of four players

592
00:29:36,936 --> 00:29:38,696
scare away up to 20 players per hour.

593
00:29:38,696 --> 00:29:42,298
And the problem with that is the math just doesn't work.

594
00:29:42,298 --> 00:29:46,199
If you ask yourself, is it okay that we allow four players

595
00:29:46,199 --> 00:29:48,439
to play at the expense of 20 players per hour,

596
00:29:48,439 --> 00:29:50,500
leaving your game entirely for the night?

597
00:29:50,500 --> 00:29:53,881
The answer to that is usually that's probably

598
00:29:53,881 --> 00:29:54,461
not a good idea.

599
00:29:54,461 --> 00:29:57,742
So what do people do about this?

600
00:29:57,742 --> 00:30:00,623
So in Halo 5, what we do is we just set our matchmaker

601
00:30:00,623 --> 00:30:02,063
to allow fair matches.

602
00:30:02,524 --> 00:30:03,885
and it won't allow unfair ones.

603
00:30:03,885 --> 00:30:06,507
So if there's not a good match for that stacked player,

604
00:30:06,507 --> 00:30:08,129
they'll end up with a very long wait.

605
00:30:08,129 --> 00:30:11,451
This ends up being better for our population overall,

606
00:30:11,451 --> 00:30:13,593
but it can be very disappointing

607
00:30:13,593 --> 00:30:15,594
to those players who'd like to play together.

608
00:30:15,594 --> 00:30:18,076
Now, other games have similar solutions.

609
00:30:18,076 --> 00:30:23,120
League of Legends, you can also result in long wait times,

610
00:30:23,120 --> 00:30:25,802
but if you're a solo or a duo player, just two of you,

611
00:30:25,802 --> 00:30:27,584
you can go into a solo-duo queue

612
00:30:27,584 --> 00:30:30,366
and play only against solo players or players of two.

613
00:30:31,035 --> 00:30:34,077
But this doesn't protect your players that are in larger parties

614
00:30:34,077 --> 00:30:35,998
that also don't want to get stomped by those.

615
00:30:35,998 --> 00:30:40,980
And it does shard the population, resulting in slightly longer matchmaking for everybody.

616
00:30:40,980 --> 00:30:43,201
Overwatch has another interesting solution.

617
00:30:43,201 --> 00:30:48,884
They basically say, no, if you are too good, you cannot play with your friends.

618
00:30:48,884 --> 00:30:51,165
They just won't even let you matchmake.

619
00:30:51,165 --> 00:30:53,787
They if you're a grandmaster and above in Overwatch,

620
00:30:53,787 --> 00:30:57,028
you're only allowed to queue either alone or with one friend.

621
00:30:58,528 --> 00:31:05,434
And this also has some relation to what sports leagues do in order to keep matches more interesting.

622
00:31:05,434 --> 00:31:14,002
They add hard or soft salary caps to promote competition. They tell teams you can only spend

623
00:31:14,002 --> 00:31:19,287
so much on your players in order to prevent these same types of issues. So it's not without

624
00:31:19,287 --> 00:31:23,091
precedent in general in competing. But again, there's no great solution here, but it is

625
00:31:23,091 --> 00:31:24,772
something to think about.

626
00:31:24,929 --> 00:31:28,158
What do you do with these stacked parties? How do you let them matchmake? How do they

627
00:31:28,158 --> 00:31:30,424
affect your population? It's worth digging into that data.

628
00:31:31,127 --> 00:31:33,990
Okay, so we've covered skill probably to death at this point.

